00:22:11,161 --> 00:22:13,123
And the idea is over time for that avatar

544
00:22:13,143 --> 00:22:15,364
to be able to be the avatar you use

545
00:22:15,384 --> 00:22:16,985
through different and distinct stories.

546
00:22:17,526 --> 00:22:22,389
So that it better sets you up to feel this identity

547
00:22:22,549 --> 00:22:26,551
that persists across episode and across the world of that

548
00:22:26,892 --> 00:22:28,393
and really takes that to a next level.

549
00:22:29,733 --> 00:22:29,833
So.

550
00:22:31,037 --> 00:22:34,320
To kind of summarize, I think everything starts with understanding your audience

551
00:22:34,881 --> 00:22:36,963
and picking a concept that that audience is going to love.

552
00:22:36,983 --> 00:22:41,328
I think then you need to embrace your medium's pacing,

553
00:22:41,789 --> 00:22:45,673
its narrative design formats, its interactivity formats,

554
00:22:46,394 --> 00:22:48,676
while at the same time taking those best practices

555
00:22:48,736 --> 00:22:50,979
from Hollywood screenwriting and keeping those in mind.

556
00:22:52,438 --> 00:22:55,220
You then want to go from a script to a build on your device

557
00:22:56,161 --> 00:22:58,963
as soon as possible, because it's really,

558
00:22:59,023 --> 00:23:01,825
the translation can be quite tricky and unexpected.

